# Project Rules

## Stack

- Use Next.js App Router.
- Use JavaScript and JSX only.
- Do not introduce TypeScript, `.tsx`, or React Router.
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling.
- Use `next/link`, `next/image`, and `next/navigation` where appropriate.

## App Structure

- `src/app` contains route files, metadata, and route-level composition.
- `src/screens` contains feature and page composition for each route.
- `src/components/ui` contains reusable UI primitives.
- `src/components/common` contains shared app shell pieces such as the navbar and footer.
- `src/data` contains static content and list data.
- `src/services` contains pure getter/helper functions for data access and filtering.
- `src/layouts` contains shared layout wrappers.

## Component Rules

- Default to server components.
- Add `"use client"` only when a component needs hooks, browser APIs, event handlers, or local state.
- Keep the client boundary as small as possible.
- Do not add `"use client"` to a file unless it is truly required.
- Prefer named exports for reusable components.
- Prefer default exports for route-level page components.

## Reuse Rules

- Check existing shared UI before creating a new component.
- Reuse existing primitives such as `SectionHeader`, `BackButton`, `ProductCard`, `GetInTouchForm`, `GetInTouchSection`, and `FAQAccordion` when they fit.
- Do not duplicate navbar or footer markup inside pages.
- `MainLayout` provides the shared shell; pages should not render `Navbar` or `Footer` directly.

## Data Rules

- Do not place reusable data arrays or objects inside component files.
- Put products, projects, news, services, careers, navigation, and other content data in `src/data`.
- Use `src/services` to read or filter data instead of repeating logic in screens.
- Treat service functions as pure helpers.

## Design Rules

- Use Tailwind utility classes and project design tokens.
- Do not hardcode raw hex colors in JSX when a token exists.
- Use the existing font and color system from the project theme.
- Keep the current visual language consistent when adding or refactoring sections.
- Preserve existing animations and interactions when moving code around.

### Page Spacing

- Desktop pages should follow the existing `container` padding of `100px`.
- On screens up to `1280px` wide, the container padding should reduce to `2rem` on the left and right.
- Keep this spacing behavior consistent for tablet/iPad and mobile layouts unless the screen already defines a more specific section-level rule.
- Do not introduce new page margin systems that fight the current container spacing.

### Color Tokens

- `navy` / `brand.navy`: `#001439` or `hsl(219 100% 11%)`
- `primary-blue` / `brand.blue`: `#2A8CD5` or `hsl(206 67% 50%)`
- `sky-accent` / `brand.sky`: `#9FCCFF` or `hsl(212 100% 81%)`
- `background`: `hsl(0 0% 100%)`
- `foreground`: `hsl(219 100% 11%)`
- `muted`: `hsl(212 60% 95%)`
- `muted-foreground`: `hsl(219 30% 46%)`
- `border` / `input`: `hsl(212 30% 88%)`
- `section-alt`: `hsl(212 60% 97%)`
- In dark mode, keep using the semantic tokens from `src/styles/index.css` instead of hardcoding new values.

### Font Tokens

- `font-sans`: `Inter, system-ui, sans-serif`
- `font-display`: `Segoe UI, system-ui, sans-serif`
- Use `font-sans` for body text and `font-display` for headings or emphasis where the project already does so.
- Keep utility text size usage consistent, including `text-md` where the project already uses it.

### Text Size

- Treat `text-md` as the default minimum text size for body copy in this project.
- Use smaller text only for compact labels, metadata, helper text, or deliberate UI details that already match the existing design.
- Do not drop below `text-md` for normal content unless the section already uses a smaller size intentionally.

## Routing Rules

- Route files in `src/app` should stay thin.
- Let route files import and render screens from `src/screens`.
- Use route params and metadata from the App Router patterns already in the project.
- Prefer static generation when the page only depends on local data.

## Quality Rules

- Keep refactors behavior-preserving unless the user asks for a change.
- If you move logic between server and client components, verify the page still builds and behaves the same.
- Run a production build after significant structural changes.
- Avoid unnecessary abstraction if the project already has a simple pattern.

## Performance Rules

- Always optimize for website performance when generating or refactoring code.
- Prefer server components, static rendering, and data-driven composition whenever possible.
- Keep client-side JavaScript as small as possible.
- Use `next/image` for images, and avoid unnecessary large client-only components.
- Defer or lazy-load heavy sections when the UX allows it.
- Avoid extra rerenders, duplicate work, and unnecessary state.
- Preserve existing animations, but keep them lightweight and purposeful.

## Working Style

- Use the existing folder structure and naming style already present in the repo.
- Keep page composition readable and small.
- Favor consistency over cleverness.
